<paragraph blockId="13.[151,642,924,950]" box="[151,642,924,950]" pageId="13" pageNumber="51">
<heading box="[151,642,924,950]" fontSize="11" level="2" pageId="13" pageNumber="51" reason="3">
<taxonomicName authority="(Pers.) K. H. Larss." box="[151,642,924,950]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Hydnodontaceae" genus="Trechispora" kingdom="Fungi" order="Trechisporales" pageId="13" pageNumber="51" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="nivea">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,296,924,950]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="51">Trechispora</emphasis>
aff. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[350,415,924,950]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="51">nivea</emphasis>
(Pers.) K.H. Larss.
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,994,1407]" pageId="13" pageNumber="51">
Basidiome resupinate, hymenial surface smooth, porulose under the lens, whitish to grayish, hyphal cords present in the hymenophore, margin indeterminate. Hyphal system monomitic, hyphae with clamps, septa ampullate in the basal hyphae and hyphal cords, smooth or encrusted with rosette-like crystal druses. Hyphal cords composed of long-celled and clamped hyphae, encrusted with rosette crystals or smooth. Cystidia absent. Basidia short cylindrical, 8–10 × 
<quantity box="[670,740,1149,1175]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="13" pageNumber="51" unit="m" value="3.5" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="3.0">3–4 µ</quantity>
m, with 4 sterigmata, and a basal clamp. Basidiospores ellipsoid, 3–3.5 × 2–2.5(–3) µm, aculeate, IKI- (
<figureCitation box="[717,804,1188,1214]" captionStart="FIGURE 13–16" captionStartId="12.[151,246,1918,1939]" captionTargetBox="[237,1381,308,1874]" captionTargetId="figure-97@12.[151,1436,265,1955]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 13–16. 13. Phanerochaete australis. 14. Phanerochaete sp. 15. Trechispora aff. nivea. 16. Vararia aff. rugosispora. a. Basidiospores. b. Basidia. c. Cystidia. ch. Hyphal cords. cr. Crystals. di. Dichohyphae. g. Gloeocystidia. h. hyphae. la. Lamprocystidia. sh. Subicular hyphae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5065966" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5065966/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="51">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="51" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,994,1407]" pageId="13" pageNumber="51">
The specimen is characterized by the smooth hymenophore, small aculeate basidiospores, and presence of druse-like crystals. It seems micromorphologically closely related to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Pers.) K. H. Larss." authorityName="K. H. Larss." baseAuthorityName="Pers." box="[980,1431,1265,1291]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Hydnodontaceae" genus="Trechispora" kingdom="Fungi" order="Trechisporales" pageId="13" pageNumber="51" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="nivea">
<emphasis box="[980,1195,1265,1290]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="51">Trechispora nivea</emphasis>
(Pers.) K.H. Larss.
</taxonomicName>
, the latter differing in the hydnoid hymenophore.
</paragraph>
